                {"src": "ellicott", "attr": "Ellicott's Commentary", "html": "<p>\"In business\" — rather, in zeal; the reference is to the spiritual life, not to practical commerce. \"Fervent\" — in the literal and etymological sense: boiling or seething. The temperament of the Christian is compared to water bubbling and boiling over the fire of the Spirit — animated, urgent, alive.</p>"},
                {"src": "calvin", "attr": "Calvin's Commentaries", "html": "<p>This precept is given not only because Christian life ought to be active, but because it often becomes us to overlook our own benefit and spend our labors in behalf of our brethren. In short, we ought in many things to forget ourselves — except we be in earnest we shall never be able to deny ourselves as Christ requires.</p>"},
                {"src": "wesley", "attr": "John Wesley's Notes", "html": "<p>Whatsoever ye do, do it with your might. In every business, diligently and fervently serving the Lord — doing all to God, not to man. The phrase \"serving the Lord\" gives the ultimate motivation: every act of zeal, however mundane its object, is an act of worship when directed toward the Lord.</p>"}
